# Project context: FamFetch (Family Inventory & Shopping List App)

You are an expert React Native (Expo) developer specializing in Supabase and Tailwind CSS.

## Core Tech Stack

- Framework: React Native with Expo (SDK)
- Routing: Expo Router (`expo-router`)
- Backend/DB: Supabase (Auth & PostgreSQL)
- Styling: Tailwind CSS (via Uniwind / NativeWind)
- UI Component Library: HeroUI Native (`heroui-native`)
- Icons: `lucide-react-native`

## Strict Guidelines & Rules

### 1. Typography (CRITICAL)

- Every time you write a `<Text>` component, you MUST include `font-noto` (for regular text) or `font-noto-bold` (for bold text) in its `className`.
- Example: `<Text className="font-noto text-base text-gray-500">Hello</Text>`
- Example: `<Text className="font-noto-bold text-lg text-black">Title</Text>`

### 2. UI Components & Layouts

- Prioritize using `heroui-native` components (e.g., Button, Card, Popover, ListGroup, Input) whenever possible to maintain a consistent UI.
- IMPORTANT: HeroUI Native uses the Compound Components pattern. For example, use `<ListGroup.ItemPrefix>` and `<ListGroup.ItemSuffix>` instead of passing `startContent` or `endContent` as props.
- Use `lucide-react-native` for all icons. Do not use `@expo/vector-icons`.
- Use Tailwind CSS (`className`) for styling. Keep it minimalist and clean.

### 3. Navigation

- Always use `expo-router` for navigation (`useRouter`, `router.push`, `router.replace`).
- Pass parameters via URL strings or objects, and retrieve them using `useLocalSearchParams()`.

### 4. Database & Logic

- Always consult `schema.sql` (if available) to understand the database structure before writing any Supabase queries.
- Write clean, type-safe TypeScript. Avoid `any` where possible.
- When deleting or modifying data (like leaving a family or transferring admin rights), always write logic that checks for edge cases (e.g., preventing the last admin from leaving without assigning a new one).

### 5. Coding Style

- Write functional, modular React components.
- Keep components concise. Separate complex logic into helper functions or hooks if necessary.
- Return early to avoid deep nesting.
